All 2760 tests pass across the full v4 suite.

**Root cause:** `regexes.cidrv6` in `packages/zod/src/v4/core/regexes.ts` used a hand-rolled pattern (`([0-9a-fA-F]{1,4})?::(...)` ) that only allowed 0–1 hex groups before `::`, unlike `regexes.ipv6`, which correctly enumerates all valid compressed forms via 8 alternatives.

**Fix:** Derived `cidrv6` from the already-correct `ipv6` regex (stripping its `^`/`$` anchors and appending the CIDR prefix-length suffix), so the two never diverge again:

```ts
export const cidrv6: RegExp = /*@__PURE__*/ new RegExp(
  `^${ipv6.source.slice(1, -1)}\\/(12[0-8]|1[01][0-9]|[1-9]?[0-9])$`
);
```

This keeps the JSON-schema `pattern` field consistent with runtime validation (which already uses `new URL()`), fixing cases like `2001:db8::/32` and `2001:db8:1::/48` without touching the runtime check path.

All 3688 tests pass across the whole `packages/zod` suite.

## Root cause

`z.default()` reuses the same default value object across every `.parse()` call. Object and array defaults were already being shallow-cloned via `util.shallowClone` (`packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts`), but that function didn't handle `Map` or `Set` — it just returned them unchanged, so every parse handed back a reference to the exact same `Map`/`Set` instance, letting mutations leak across calls.

## Fix

`packages/zod/src/v4/core/util.ts` — extended `shallowClone` to clone `Map` and `Set` instances too:

```ts
export function shallowClone(o: any): any {
  if (isPlainObject(o)) return { ...o };
  if (Array.isArray(o)) return [...o];
  if (o instanceof Map) return new Map(o);
  if (o instanceof Set) return new Set(o);
  return o;
}
```

This is used by both the classic and mini API's `_default`/`_prefault` implementations, so both benefit. All 4 previously-failing tests in `default.test.ts` now pass, and the full `packages/zod` suite (3688 tests) still passes.
